        Floor Area vs Land Area in Brisbane Property Valuation: Which Drives Price More?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Sellers often compare floor area when benchmarking value, but in Brisbane's inner east land area frequently does more of the work. Here is how to read both numbers correctly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When sellers begin to think about what their home is worth, they almost always compare it to recent sales: a similar house up the road that sold last month, a slightly larger one two streets over that sold for a higher figure, a smaller one that sold for less. That comparison process is the right starting point, but it tends to lean on whichever number the seller can most easily find in the listing copy, which is usually floor area or bedroom count. In Brisbane's inner east, the more important number is often land area. The interaction between floor area, land area, location, condition, and improvements is what actually sets price, and sellers who understand the relative weight of each variable produce more accurate expectations than sellers who do not.</p>

      <p>This article walks through how floor area and land area each contribute to value, why land tends to dominate in established inner suburbs, the specific situations where floor area takes the lead, the per-square-metre comparisons that mislead, and a practical framework for benchmarking value sensibly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What land area actually represents</h2>
      <p>Land area is the size of the parcel itself. In Brisbane's inner east, land is the scarce, finite, ultimately appreciating asset. It cannot be added to (the title boundaries are fixed); it cannot be replicated (the suburb is built out); and its location characteristics (street, orientation, slope, frontage, river proximity, transport access) are essentially permanent. The home built on the land can be renovated, extended, demolished, or rebuilt; the land itself cannot. For this reason, valuers and experienced agents tend to treat land as the foundational component of value in established inner suburbs, with the building functioning as a near-term contributor that depreciates over time relative to the land beneath it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What floor area actually represents</h2>
      <p>Floor area is the total internal area of the building. It captures bedrooms, living areas, kitchens, bathrooms, garages (sometimes), and any other enclosed space. It correlates with utility (more area means more rooms, larger rooms, more storage) and with the cost of building (every additional square metre cost something to construct). Floor area drives running costs as well, with larger homes typically costing more to heat, cool, clean, insure, and maintain. From a buyer-utility perspective, floor area is genuinely important; from a long-term value perspective, it is meaningful but usually subordinate to land area in established suburbs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why land typically dominates in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>In suburbs like Bulimba, Hawthorne, Norman Park, Cannon Hill, and Carina, the land component of total property value frequently exceeds the building component, often substantially. A three-bedroom timber Queenslander on 800 square metres of land in a desirable street can be worth more than a four-bedroom new-build on 405 square metres in the same suburb, because the larger block is the rarer asset and the smaller block carries an irreversible constraint. Buyers who are sophisticated about long-term value (developers, knock-down-rebuild buyers, owner-occupiers thinking five-to-ten years ahead) tend to weight land area more heavily than the listing photos suggest, and the market clears at prices that reflect that weighting.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When floor area takes the lead</h2>
      <p>There are situations in which floor area is the dominant value driver. Apartments and townhouses (where the land component is shared and effectively spread across multiple titles) trade primarily on floor area, layout, and location. Newer detached homes on small subdivided blocks trade more heavily on floor area because the land component is small and uniform across comparables. Homes in price-bracketed segments where buyers are functionally constrained on bedroom count (four or more bedrooms for a family of five, for example) can see floor area drive the sale price more than land. Buyers in these segments are essentially buying the building first and the land second, and the seller's marketing should reflect that.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The per-square-metre comparison and its limits</h2>
      <p>Sellers and buyers sometimes try to compare properties using a per-square-metre figure: total price divided by floor area, or total price divided by land area. These figures have a useful diagnostic role but are easily misinterpreted. A high per-square-metre-of-floor-area figure can simply mean the home is small but well placed; a low figure can mean the home is large but poorly configured. A high per-square-metre-of-land figure can mean the block is small but in a premium street; a low figure can mean the block is large but on a busy road. Both numbers compress too many variables into a single ratio to be reliable on their own. They are useful as cross-checks against more nuanced comparable analysis, not as a primary valuation method.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Land shape and usable area matter as much as raw size</h2>
      <p>An 800-square-metre block with a regular rectangular shape, level grade, and useful frontage is meaningfully more valuable than an 800-square-metre block with an awkward irregular shape, a steep grade, and a narrow frontage. The same total land area carries different practical possibilities. Buyers (and valuers) implicitly adjust for this: they look at the front-to-back depth, the side setback room, the slope, the orientation, the usable garden area, and the building envelope a future renovation or rebuild could legally occupy. Sellers benchmarking against comparable sales should look at land shape and usability, not just the total square-metre figure on the title.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The orientation effect on usable land</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's climate, orientation interacts with usable land in ways that show up in price. A north-facing back garden lets winter sun into living areas and shelters outdoor spaces from the hottest western sun in summer, which makes the same garden area meaningfully more usable across the year than a south-facing equivalent. A west-facing back garden absorbs harsh afternoon heat that limits outdoor entertaining in the warmer months. East-facing gardens are pleasant in the morning and shaded by mid-afternoon, which suits some buyers and not others. The same 200 square metres of usable garden carries different value depending on the orientation, and sellers should factor this into their comparable analysis rather than treating land area as a flat number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building age, condition, and the depreciation curve</h2>
      <p>The building component of value depreciates over time relative to the land beneath it. A well-maintained timber home that is fifty years old is rarely worth what it cost to build in today's dollars, regardless of how comfortable it is to live in. Buyers and valuers implicitly apply a depreciation curve, asking how much of the building's useful life remains, what major capital items (roof, plumbing, electrical, kitchen, bathrooms) are nearing replacement, and how much the next owner is likely to spend in the first five years. A larger floor area on an ageing building does not always translate to a higher price; the floor area may be discounted by the buyer's renovation arithmetic. Land, by contrast, does not depreciate; if anything, the long-run trend is the other way.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why developer interest amplifies the land effect</h2>
      <p>In several Brisbane inner east suburbs, knock-down-rebuild and small-scale developer buyers are an active and persistent component of the buyer pool, particularly for blocks of 600 square metres or more in well-positioned streets. These buyers value the land near-exclusively and treat the existing dwelling as either a temporary holding asset or a write-off. Their willingness to pay sets a floor price for the land component independent of the building, and that floor price quietly underpins the broader market. Sellers of larger inner-east blocks should understand that even if their owner-occupier marketing focuses on the existing home, a non-trivial slice of the buyer pool is doing land-value arithmetic in the background.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to benchmark sensibly against recent sales</h2>
      <p>Begin with a like-for-like comparable: same suburb, similar land area, similar building age and configuration, sold in the last six to twelve months. From there, adjust for the differences that actually matter: street quality, land shape and slope, orientation, building condition, kitchen and bathroom standard, outdoor connection, parking, and any structural points (subsidence, retaining walls, easements). Resist the temptation to anchor on a single per-square-metre figure; the better discipline is to start with three or four genuinely comparable sales, identify the variables in which your property differs, and adjust upwards or downwards accordingly. An experienced agent runs this exercise routinely and is the right collaborator for a serious benchmarking conversation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical framework for sellers</h2>
      <p>For detached homes in Brisbane's inner east, treat land area as the foundation and floor area as the modifier. For townhouses and apartments, treat floor area as the foundation and the location component (level, aspect, building amenities) as the modifier. In both cases, look beyond the headline numbers: shape, slope, orientation, condition, and street quality each move price in ways the per-square-metre figures do not capture. The more variables you account for explicitly, the closer your expectation will sit to the price the buyer pool ultimately settles on, and the smaller the gap between the listing campaign and the contract.</p>

